        "text": "[1] A detailed review of processes, status, and projected changes of wildfires in the Arctic can be found in McCarty et al. (2021) and in Meredith et al. (2019).\n\n[2] Further information about the Global Fire Assimilation System (GFAS) dataset and the monitoring of wildfires by the Copernicus Atmosphere Monitoring Service (CAMS) is provided in a list of Q&As on their website.\n\n[3] According to the WMO State of the Global Climate 2023 report, the total area burned by wildfires in Canada in 2023 was 14.9 million hectares; well above the previous record of 6.7 million hectares set in 1989.\n\n[4] In the map shown in Figure 2, wildfire locations are shown only where the GFAS-estimated wildfire radiative power is greater than or equal to 1 W/m2.\n\n[5] An analysis of climatic factors contributing to Arctic wildfire activity can be found in Masrur et al. (2018).\n\n[6] An example of the darkening effect of aerosol emissions from the burning of boreal forests was documented for the Greenland ice sheet by Thomas et al. (2017)."
